 that are registered for reflection and if that was the case here. It seems we have the DMLERR_NO_ERROR field in the library metadata, so f.getInt should be called. But if the initial report showed getFields covered yet Field#getInt remains uncovered, what’s going on? \\n\\nMaybe in the Native Image, Ddeml.class.getFields did return fields but only for DMLERR_FIRST/LAST. I should inspect the report further to find out why the loop didn’t reach getInt due to class initialization issues.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating Field.getInt behavior**\\n\\nWhen Field.getInt is called on DMLERR_NO_ERROR, it seems to trigger the initialization of the Ddeml interface, which executes INSTANCE Native.load for user32. But on Linux, since there’s no user32, it throws an UnsatisfiedLinkError when attempting Field#getInt. I wonder if the dynamic call should be processed before encountering this error. Instrumentation might only count tracked API calls if they successfully return, which adds another layer to this issue. I'm really curious how this plays out!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Troubleshooting library loading**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out why `getFields` is covered but `getInt` isn't. It might be that `getFields` has no matching fields or fails somehow? But the test throws an `UnsatisfiedLinkError`, potentially from `DdemlUtil.DdemlException.create`. I’m questioning how `getFields` could work while `getInt` doesn’t if there’s a failure. Maybe we need to conduct tests on Linux? I wonder if creating a mock could help, or if JNA can be adjusted to avoid loading the native library unnecessarily.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class initialization**\\n\\nI’m wondering if `Field.getInt(null)` triggers class initialization. According to the JLS, reflective access for static fields does trigger initialization, which means that's likely true. I’m considering preconfiguring JNA to avoid loading with options like `Native.setProtected` or `jna.nounpack`, but those don't seem to work. Maybe I could use a fake library for \\\"user32,\\\" but that seems tough. It looks like we have to suppress `Ddeml.INSTANCE` initialization. The interface fields get initialized in a specific order, which complicates things. I think I need to run some experiments to see if anything changes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Native Image coverage**\\n\\nI need to understand how the Native Image coverage process works, especially since the latest report only covered `getFields`. The `DdemlException` indicates that the class initialization was executed, but `getFields` returned zero fields, possibly because it was only querying public fields. It seems the metadata in the current report might come from an external workflow. There have been two attempts without new coverage, which suggests our changes may have caused a test failure. I’m pondering whether `Field#getInt` remains uncovered because the native-image metadata isn’t included in the main metadata, despite adding all public fields.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_VSGAdKaFrDX0CtrWZ3kNwBaA|fc_0bbb39c135ee2d310169f984dfab008196aba978694e50fd80", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/net.java.dev.jna/jna-platform/5.3.1 -type f | sort && git diff -- tests/src/net.java.dev.jna/jna-platform/5.3.1/src/test/java/net_java_dev_jna/jna_platform/DdemlUtilInnerDdemlExceptionTest.java tests/src/net.java.dev.jna/jna-platform/5.3.1/src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image/reachability-metadata.json metadata/net.java.dev.jna/jna-platform/5.3.1/reachability-metadata.json | sed -n '1,240p'", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 5958, "output": 1327, "cacheRead": 29696, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 36981, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777960139159, "responseId": "resp_0bbb3